Let's think step by step. First, recall that the smallest prime number greater than 2 is 3. Second, list all the 5-distinct-prime sums less than 100 and check if any of them are prime:

\begin{align*}
&2+3+5+7+11=28& \rightarrow &\text{Not prime}\\
&2+3+5+7+13=30& \rightarrow &\text{Not prime}\\
&2+3+5+7+17=34& \rightarrow &\text{Not prime}\\
&2+3+5+7+19=36& \rightarrow &\text{Not prime}\\
&2+3+5+11+13=34& \rightarrow &\text{Not prime}\\
&2+3+5+11+17=37& \rightarrow &\text{Prime!}
\end{align*}

So, yes, 37 is a smaller prime number that can be written as a sum of 5 distinct primes. The answer is E.
